#Approach:

Next Permutation – Approach

Sabse pehle array ko right se traverse karke first aisa index find karo
jaha nums[i] < nums[i+1] ho.
Is index ko breakpoint bolte hain.
Yahi wo position hoti hai jahan next greater permutation banana possible hota hai.

Agar aisa breakpoint na mile, matlab array pure descending order me hai
aur wo already last permutation hai.
Is case me poora array reverse kar do taki smallest permutation mil jaye.

Agar breakpoint mil jaye, to right side se first aisa element dhoondo
jo breakpoint wale element se bada ho.
Usse swap kar do.

Swap ke baad breakpoint ke right wala part descending order me hota hai,
isliye us part ko reverse kar do taki wo smallest possible order me aa jaye.

Is tarah hume current arrangement se just next lexicographically greater permutation mil jata hai.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)

#Code:

class Solution {

    private void swap(int[] nums, int a, int b){
        int temp = nums[a];
        nums[a] = nums[b];
        nums[b] = temp;
    }

    private void reverse(int[] nums, int start, int end){
        while(start < end){
            int temp = nums[start];
            nums[start] = nums[end];
            nums[end] = temp;
            start++;
            end--;
        }
    }

    public void nextPermutation(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;
        int idx = -1;
        for(int i=n-2; i>=0; i--){
            if(nums[i] < nums[i+1]){
                idx = i;
                break;
            }
        }

        if(idx == -1){
            reverse(nums, 0, n-1);
            return;
        }

        //otherwise
        for(int i=n-1; i>= idx+1; i--){
            if(nums[i] > nums[idx]){
                swap(nums, i, idx);
                break;
            }
        }

        reverse(nums, idx+1, n-1);
        
    }
}
